const KNOWLEDGE_BASE = "\n\n===== Lecture 1 - Introduction =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 1\nTopics:\nEU Floods Directive (Directive 2007/60/EC)\nPrograms of Measures in accordance with the Floods Directive\nFlood Damage Potentials\nResearch Program RIMAX\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\n... and you understand the relationship with the EU Water Framework Directive (EU-WFD).\nYou know about the three phase approach of the EU Floods Directive ...\nYou perform autonomously the necessary tasks in the context of the Floods Directive ...\n... and you evaluate the results regarding flood damage and flood risks.\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDefinitions Flood & Flood Risk\n... is the temporary covering by water of land, that usually is not covered by water.\nFlood\nFlood risk\nSource: EU Floods Directive\nSource: \u00a772 German Federal Water Act\n... is the likelihood of a flood event of a certain extent, combined with the estimated damage in terms of \nhuman health, the environment and economic activity associated with a flood event of that extent.\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDefinition Flood Protection\nFlood Protection\nSource: German DIN 4047 Part 1 (Agricultural Hydraulic Engineering) \n... Entirety of the measures of the waterway construction through water control and the installation of dikes, \nthe flood retention and / or the structural changes to vulnerable buildings and facilities \nthat serve to minimize the flood plain, to reduce the flood water level and / or to reduce the flood \ndischarge.\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk\nOne possible definition of a flood risk:\nThe product of\nthe probability of occurrence (of the runoff event)\n&\nthe extent of damage (of the runoff event)\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk according to the German Federal Water Act (WHG)\nFlood risk\n... is the combination of the probability of a flood event with the possible adverse flood consequences for \nhuman health,\nthe environment,\ncultural heritage,\neconomic activities and\nconsiderable material assets\nSource: \u00a7 73 German Federal Water Act\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRisk Elements\n... are the real-world objects that can be negatively affected by a (flood) hazard.\n... examples for risk elements:\nresidential and commercial buildings\ninfrastructure (roads, canals etc.)\ncultural heritage\nconservation areas\nand of course the human being\n... Risk elements are often aggregated. (e.g. all single-family houses in a survey area)\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDamage\n... is the opposite of a benefit\n... is the material (or ideal) deterioration of a risk element\n... can be subdivided into different categories with different units, such as:  \nProperty damages in money\nNumber of casualties\nEnvironmental damage which cannot (in most cases) be monetized\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Management Cycle\nPrevention\nProtection\nPreparedness\nEmergency \nresponse\nRecovery\nReview\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFuture Flood Protection\nNatural \nwater retention\nTechnical \nflood protection\nFar-reaching\nflood precautions\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFuture Flood Protection - a Matter of Balance\nNatural \nflood \nprotection\nEconomic \ngrowth\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFuture Flood Protection - a Matter of Balance\nEconomic\ngrowth\nNatural \nflood\nprotection\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThe 3 Steps of the EU Floods Directive \n\u2022\nPreliminary flood risk assessment\nCompletion by the end of 2011\n\u2022\nFlood Risk Maps\nCompletion by the end of 2013\n\u2022\nPlans for flood risk management\nCompletion and publication by the end of 2015\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStep I: Preliminary Flood Risk Assessment\n\u2022 Map of the river basin districts including general descriptions\n\u2022 Documentation of historical flood events\n\u2022 Description of the general flood characteristics \n(first-order processes, characteristic flood plains and flood conveyance routes)\n\u2022 Documentation of the development plans \n(change of land use, distribution of the population and of the economic sectors, \nflood risk for the up- and downstream riparian area)\n\u2022 Evaluation of the probability of future flood events\n\u2022 Forecast of the impact of future flood events\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStep II: Flood Risk Maps\n\u2022 Flood plain mapping\n(based on the scenarios HQ10, HQ100 and HQEx)\nEssential elements to name:\n\u2013\nWater depths\n\u2013\nFlow velocities\n\u2013\nAreas with bank erosion and debris\n\u2022 Flood Damage Maps \n(including information about the affected residents and the environmental damage)\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStep III: Plans for Flood Risk Management\n\u2022 Plans to reduce the flood risk\n(including the consequences on human health, the environment and the economic activities)\n\u2022 Activities must take into account the full range of flood risk management measures\n(prevention, protection, preparedness) \n\u2022 Measures which increase the risk of flooding for the down- and upstream riparians are excluded\n\u2022 Measures to reduce the flood risk are not prescribed\n\u2022 Criticism: No deadline exists for the implementation of the action plans\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRequirements to the Floods Directive\nThe contents of the stages II and III have to be aligned to the requirements of the EU Water Framework Directive: \n\u2022 Environmental objectives (Article 4)\n\u2022 Programs of measures (Article 11)\n\u2022 Management plans for the river basins (Article 13)\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nOrganizational Aspects: Floods Directive & EU Water Framework Directive\nThese organizational aspects run synchronously in both directives:\n\u2022\nSpatial subdivision\n\u2022\nCompetent authority\n\u2022\nSchedule for implementation and repetition periods\n\u2022\nReporting mechanisms\n\u2022\nPublic participation\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nManagement Plans & Programs of Measures according to EU-WFD\n\u2022 have to contain cost-effective combinations of measures to achieve the goal\n\u2022 have to be presented to the public in advance\n\u2022 are specified by the regulations of the state water laws \n\u2022 originally did not have mandatory contents regarding the topic \"flood\"\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Plain Zoning\nZone\nPlants\nAnimals\nAquatic\nUnder water level\nAmphibious\nWater exchange\nTerrestrial\nAbove water level\nWater crowfoot\nPondweed\nWater starwort\nGoosefoot\nKnotweed\nReed\nStinging nettle\nFish\nWater insects\nAmphibians\nDragonflies\nSoftwood meadow\nHardwood meadow\nFlood\nWetlands and biological communities\nneed periodic flooding\nfor the preservation of the composition of their species\nImage Quote: C\u00fcppers, German Association of Water Protection, Vol 66\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFrom the Actual State to the Mission Statement according to EU-WFD\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Damage Potential of the Rhine\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Damage Potential of the Rhine\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample Map: Flood Hazard Map of the river Ruhr\nImage Quote:  ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRIMAX\n38 cooperation projects with more than 100 partners\n\u2013 65% science\n\u2013 20% small and medium enterprises\n\u2013 15% administration\nOverall coordination:\nGeoForschungsZentrum Potsdam (GFZ)\nSection 5.4: Engineering Hydrology\nIn cooperation with CEDIM - University of Karlsruhe\nRisk Management of Extreme Flood Events\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRIMAX: Transfer into Practice\ndownload: \nhttp://www.rimax-hochwasser.de\nFlood forecasting (Prof. Disse) \nOperational Flood Management (Prof. Pasche) \nRisk management (Prof. Meon) \nRisk communication (Prof. Gr\u00fcnewald) \nDikes (Prof. Bieberstein)\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nClimate change and EU-WFD\n\u2022 Climate change is considered to be an environmental impact of human activities \n(as defined in Article 5 of the EU-WFD) \n\u2022 Thus, climate change is incorporated in the tasks of the EU-Water Framework Directive \n\u2022 Reference conditions of water bodies are to be adjusted to the effects of climate change\n\u2022 The action plans are to be adjusted to the required adaptation strategies in order to be cost-effective\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nEuropean Floods (1998 - 2005)\nImage Quote: EEA 2007\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImage Quote:  European Commission - Green Paper to adapt to climate change\nChange in the HQ100 Discharges in Europe\nReference period 2080\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThe European Commission Green Paper\n\u2022 Measures to combat climate change are supposed to be implemented in the Water Framework Directive\n\u2022 The necessary adaptation strategies to climate change are included in the planning of measures in accordance \nwith the EU Floods Directive\n\u2022 This was already supposed to be implemented within the implementation period in 2009\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nEU Floods Directive and EU Water Framework Directive\nFlood aspects\nEcology\nEconomy\nClimate change\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n\u2026 No Rule without Exception\nImage Quote: Ehapa-Verlag\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nA different kind of Flood Risk Management\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nA different kind of Flood Risk Management\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThe Rheinauhafen in Cologne (Germany)\nUnderground car park\nLength: 1,2 Km\nImage: Google Maps\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License \n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCourse Flood Risk Management  | Lecture 1 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 2 - Awareness-Raising =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 2\nTopics:\nCommunication in Flood Risk Management\nAdvantages and Disadvantages of Classical and Internet-Based Approaches\nInformal Learning through Serious Gaming\nExamples of Information Services for Flood Risk Management\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nYou are aware of different methods of communication with public \u2026.\n\u2026 and will choose the appropriate method to do so.\nYou know about serious games as method for informal learning \u2026.\n\u2026 and make use of them to inform public about flood risk.\nYou understand the advantages of apps to inform about flood risk subjects.\nYou design methods for increasing the risk awareness of the population and apply them independently.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCommunication in Flood Risk Management\nCommunication\n=\nExchange or transference of information\nWhat is it all about ???\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nWhat do we communicate? [A misleading example]\nFlood Protection\n\u201cEntirety of the measures of the waterway construction through water control and the installation\nof dikes, the flood retention and / or the structural changes to vulnerable buildings and facilities\nthat serve to minimize the flood plain, to reduce the flood water level and / or to reduce the flood\ndischarge.\u201d\nSource: DIN 4047 Part 1 (Agricultural Hydraulic Engineering)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nClassical designation of Flood Areas: an example\nImage Quote: AVZ / AN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nChange in communication in the event of flooding\nWhat went well in 2013:\n- 24-hour Liveticker (seek help, find help)\n- Guide for flood affected residents\n- App for flood levels\nWhat did not went well:\n- Error messages in social media\n- Contradiction in social media\n- The user claim: information every minute\nInternet usage during the\nElbe floodings 2002/2013\n2002\n18 million hits (only on web pages)\n2013\n91 million hits (mobile devices)\nImage Quote: MDR, Mr. Jahny\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nA good example: Flood Aid Dresden [a private initiative]\nTarget: Connecting helpers with people seeking help\nNo Target: Informing general public\nImage Quote: Fluthilfe Dresden\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: Flood Aid Dresden\nImage Quote: Fluthilfe Dresden\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: Flood Aid Dresden [Suggesting a Candidate for the Flood Helpers Medal]\nImage Quote: Fluthilfe Dresden\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nSource:\nSerious Games as a tool for Informal Learning\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: Damage Visualization [SchaVis]\n\"The game SchaVIS ... is a digital visualization system for flood\ndamages to buildings.\nIt is supposed to give the affected persons the opportunity to learn\nplayfully about flood prevention.\nThe game offers four scenarios of varying difficulty. One playing\nsequence takes approximately 20 minutes.\u201c\nImage Quote: Schavis\n\u2026 unfortunately no longer available online\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: SimFlood\n\"SimFlood is an online computer game in which the players take the role of flood-prone home owners who have\nto decide whether and at what price they want to protect themselves against the risk of flooding. \"\nSource: University of Karlsruhe, Institute of Insurance Sciences\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: SeCom2.0 \u2013 LFI RWTH Aachen\nImage Quote: Secom LFI\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nSeCom2.0:\nImage Quote: Secom LFI\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: HQ50 - Saxony Flood Control Center\nImage Quote: https://howapro.de/howa-hq50-game\n\u201cThe serious game \u201cHQ50 \u2013 Flooding in Your Community\u201d serves as\na playful and visually appealing element during the training.\nThe game was designed and implemented in collaboration with a\nmedia educator and a team specializing in game design. It conveys\nlearning content on the topic of flooding in an entertaining way.\nThe overarching goal of the game is to raise awareness of the topic\nof flooding and draw attention to specific issues in the event of\nflooding.\nThese include, for example, dealing with uncertainties in forecasts or\nkeeping alarm and emergency plans up to date.\u201d\n\u2026 unfortunately the game is only available in German Language\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: Stop Disasters - UNDRR\nImage Quote: https://www.stopdisastersgame.org/\nThis game focuses on risks in general, not only on the flood topic.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPractical Exercise\nOn our premises, you have the option of\nerecting such a mobile flood protection\nwall yourself under supervision.\nImage Quote: LFI\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nAvatar based teaching and learning: How to build a mobile flood protection wall\nIn addition we offer you the\npossibility to build a mobile flood\nprotection wall with our VR software.\nMore info: MyScore website\nVideo Quote: https://myscore.lfi.rwth-aachen.de/\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n... how can I inform myself about Hazards and Risks?\nImage Quotes: Apple App Store\nThe following list provides an overview of available apps. These contain updated information about\nexisting water management threats and risks.\nDWD app for Germany with precipitation radar information, weather alerts and warnings about\nfloods, storm surges and avalanches\nWarnwetter\nWetteronline-App with exhaustive precipitation radar data\nRegenRadar\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n... how can I inform myself about Hazards and Risks?\nApp of the transnational flood portal, indicating the current water levels at the gauges of the\nindividual states and notification stages\nApp of the State Agency for Flood Defence and Water Management of Saxony-Anhalt with online\nflood hazard maps\nApp of the Federal Office for Civil Protection and Disaster Assistance with civil protection\nincluding alerts, weather warnings and flood information\nMeinPegel\nHochwasser-\ngefahrST\nNINA\nOnline information about water level data in Germany, Austria and Switzerland\nPegelalarm\nImage Quotes: Apple App Store\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 2 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License\n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even\ncommercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 3 - Historical Flood Events =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 3\nTopics:\nHistorical Documents regarding Risk Management\nHistorical Flood Water Marks\nDocumentation of Flood Areas\nAerial Picture Archives and Photo Documentation\nStipulations in Historical Water Laws\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\nYou understand the relevance of historical floods for the derivation of measures for the implementation\nof the EU Floods Directive.\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRelation to the European Floods Directive [Directive 2007/60/EC]\nThe EU Floods Directive directly refers to historical floods.\nArticle 4, Paragraph 2:\nThe preliminary assessment of flood risk should be based on available or easily derivable information.\nRequired Content (Excerpts):\n\u2022 \u201cA description of past floods which had significant adverse effects on human health, the environment,\ncultural heritage and economic activity and for which the likelihood of recurrence in a similar form is still\nexistent, including their extent and conveyance routes and an assessment of the adverse impact\u201d\n\u2022 \u201cA description of the significant floods of the past where significant adverse consequences similar to\nfuture events might be expected\u201c\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStrategy for Implementing the EU Floods Directive\nThe directive has a great deal of flexibility in terms of how to deal with historical floods.\nIt is only required to describe historical floods with significant adverse consequences in order to preliminarily\nassess the flood risk.\nThe description could be made in a verbal form. Already existing and availabel documents (e.g. water\nmanagement framework plans, maps) might also have been used.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nEngineering versus Humanities\nWhen integrating historical floods Engineering should rely on classical techniques of Humanities.\nResearch Area: Historical technical and environmental research\nWorking methods used:\nExpertise and experience in data acquisition and source-critical analysis of handwritten or printed archive\nmaterials on \"Hydraulic Engineering / Water Management\" (for the period from 1500 to 1950) in archives and\nresearch libraries\nSource: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge\nHumanities\nEngineering\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Marks\nImage Quote: Fournier\nVietnam Hoi An\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Marks: River Main, Frankfurt\nPicture Quote: Jahrhundertflut 1342\nPicture Quote:\nGoogle Maps\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Marks: River Weser, Hannoversch M\u00fcnden\nPicture Quote: Jahrhundertflut 1342\nPicture Quote:\nGoogle Maps\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Marks\nPirna / Elbe\nin Dessau / well\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge 2005\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge 2005\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Marks: web-based Information Portal Saxony\nPirna / Elbe\nin Dessau / well\nImage Quotes: Umwelt Sachsen\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Areas I\nExample of a flood documentation related to\nthe river on the Elbe\nEvent September 1890\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge; City Archive Pirna\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Flood Areas II\nExample of a historical map of a flood\ninundation in the river system of the Saale\nReference year: 1920\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nAerial Documentation\nFlooding of the Mulde close to Je\u00dfnitz\nJanuary 1932\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge; LHASA, Abt. Dessau\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPhoto Documentation\nLeine \u2013 Flooding in G\u00f6ttingen (February 1909)\nImage Quote: Deutsch &\nP\u00f6rtge\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Water Laws\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge\nWater Law\nof the Kingdom of Saxony as of 1909\n\u201cThe parties must be informed by public notice that certain municipalities are due to\nset the flood inundation line.\nThe plan must be interpreted publicly by the managing authority for at least three\nmonths before the final establishing of the flood inundation area.\u201d\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Water Laws\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge; Saxon State Archives Chemnitz.\nAmtshauptmannschaft Plauen\nRoyal Saxon Ministry of the Interior 1909\n\u201c\u2026 in general, exact geometric plans on a scale of\n1: 1000 to 1: 2000 are required, which allow a reliable processing and\naccurate transfer of the found lines in nature or from nature into the\nplans.\u201d\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Water Laws\nImage Quote: Deutsch & P\u00f6rtge\nPrussian law collection 1913\nWithout permission not alloweded in deep areas:\n\u2022\nIncrease of the earth's surface and production, extension and installation of\nplants that extend beyond the earth's surface\n\u2022\nto eliminate dikes, dams and other dike-like elevations in whole or in part\nClearance of the flood area of watercourses\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 3 | Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License\n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons-License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 4 - Flood Action Plans =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 4\nTopics:\nBasics & Definitions regarding Flood Action Plans \nExamples of Action Plans in NRW\nContents of Flood Action Plans \n(Inventory, Hydrology, Hydraulics, Damage Potentials)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\n... and you explain the various flood protection measures of the Action Plans.\nYou know the various precautionary principles ...\nYou apply the process of a damage potential analysis for a specific task.\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nReasons for the Flood Action Plans I\nThe concrete implementation idea for the Flood Action Plans was i.a. based on the following flood events:\n\u2022\nThe Rhine floods in 1993, 1995 and 1999\n\u2022\nThe Oder flood in 1997\n\u2022\nThe Whitsun flood in Bavaria 1999\n\"Guidelines for Forward-Looking Integrated Flood Protection \u201c (LAWA 1995)\nAlongside measures to improve natural retention and technical flood control, the main elements of the \nguidelines were: \n\u2022\nArea-related precautions\n\u2022\nBuilding precautions\n\u2022\nRisk precautions\n\u2022\nBehavioral precautions & provision of information\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nReasons for the Flood Action Plans II\nIn the 53th Conference of Environment Ministers in 1999, the recommendations for a sustainable and future-\noriented flood protection have been postulated.\nThese recommendations were based on a three pillar model:\n\u2022\nPreventive flood protection (flood area management)\n\u2022\nTechnical flood protection\n\u2022\nFurther flood prevention (Building and risk precautions)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nReasons for the Flood Action Plans III\nThe German Federal States' Working Group on Water (LAWA) has compiled and published subsequently in 1999 \nthe \"recommendation for the preparation of Flood Action Plans\u201d.\nThe action targets of this nationwide recommendation included:\n\u2022 Reducing damage risks\n\u2022 Reducing flood water levels\n\u2022 Reinforcing flood awareness\n\u2022 Improving the flood early warning system\nThis recommendation for action should ensure a harmonized approach as well as the comparability of the \nresults.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Control Act\n\"Act to improve preventive flood control\" (Flood Control Act 2005)\nThe Flood Control Act stipulated \nthat flood areas [based on a 100-year flood]\n& \nflood-prone areas \nare supposed to be marked in the spatial plans, the land use plans and in the development plans.\nAs result of an analysis, it was found that the \"flood control thinking and promise\u201c should rather be directed to \nthe sober and factual \"dealing with the risk\u201c.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nReasons for the Flood Action Plans IV\nIn 2006 the state NRW has created a flood protection concept focusing on the following areas:\n\u2022\nFlood Area Management\nUses are supposed to be limited if ecological and economic reasons oppose flood protection measures.\nThe degree of the protection against flooding should be adapted to the local damage potential.\n\u2022\nFlood precautions\n\u2022\nPrevention of flood damage\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nOverview of the Flood Action Plans in NRW\nLeadership/ employer:\nDistrict governments \n(formerly State environmental agencies)\nCreation:\nEngineering companies\nCollaboration:\nLocal water boards, municipalities\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood-Prone Areas\nThe Flood Action Plans contained verbal and cartographic description of the flood-prone areas of the river \nplains. \nIt was required that all areas that can be flooded should be designated.\nThe recommendation called for the following descriptions:\n\u2022\nLegally determined flood areas\n\u2022\nTechnically defined flood areas (e.g. determination by past flooding or computational determination)\n\u2022\nFlood-prone areas behind dikes/ protective walls \n\u2022\nFlood-prone areas downstream of dams after the use of flood relief spillways\n\u2022\nAreas with other legal protection statuses\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Protection\nThe Flood Action Plans had to provide information on the existing flood protection. \nBoth the water retention in the catchment area and the technical flood protection had to be considered.\nAt the same time, information on the protection level of flood protection (in the form of return periods) was \nrequired.\nWith regards to \u200bflood prevention the four components\n\u2022\narea-based precaution\n\u2022\nbuilding precaution\n\u2022\nbehavioral precaution\n\u2022\nrisk precaution\nwere to be investigated and documented.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMeasures in Flood Action Plans I\nIn the Flood Action Plans concrete measures were required that contribute to flood protection. \nDifferent categories of measures had to be taken into account. \nMeasures to increase the natural retention were considered to be of paramount importance.\nThe recommendation states the following examples:\n\u2022\nPrevention and / or unsealing of sealed surfaces\n\u2022\nDecentralized infiltration of the runoff from sealed areas\n\u2022\nNatural-like development and design of water bodies\n\u2022\nElimination / reduction of unnecessary drainage ditches\n\u2022\nExtensification of land management, land lying fallow, promotion of conservative soil management\n\u2022\nSite-specific afforestation of agricultural land\n\u2022\nRetention through hollows and barriers\n\u2022\nRecovery of areas for flood retention and flood runoff\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMeasures in Flood Action Plans II\nIn addition to the natural retention, measures for technical flood control were also supposed to be included in \nthe Action Plans. The following categories and specific measures that could also be implemented simultaneously \nhave been addressed:\nMeasures for water retention\n\u2022\nRetention basins in the water body\n\u2022\nFlood polders along the river\n\u2022\nFlood water retention areas in multi-purpose reservoirs\nMeasures in flood-prone areas\n\u2022\nChanges in cross sectional profile\n\u2022\nChanges in longitudinal profile, changes in the water course\n\u2022\nFlood channels\n\u2022\nDikes, walls \n\u2022\nMobile protection elements\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMeasures in Flood Action Plans III\nAnother category in the Flood Action Plans were measures for flood prevention (including land, building, \nbehavioral and risk precautions).\nThe recommendation suggests the following possible measures:\n\u2022\nDetermination of flood areas\n\u2022\nInforming the population about their individual risk of flooding\n\u2022\nRecording and permanently marking known flood levels\n\u2022\nUpdating the provision of flood information\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMeasures in Flood Action Plans IV\nOther possible measures:\n\u2022\nImprovement of the flood forecasting and the flood information system\n\u2022\nSetting up and updating alarm and operational plans\n\u2022\nPracticing the protective measures with emergency services and the affected residents\n\u2022\nTraining emergency personnel\n\u2022\nSupply and maintenance of technical aids\n\u2022\nInclusion of a risk provision by means of insurance coverage of potentially affected people\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMeasures in Flood Action Plans V\nFinally, all the planned measures had to be summarized in a catalog of measures.\nEach measure has been assigned to one of the categories listed below:\n\u2022\nWater retention in the catchment area\n\u2022\nWater retention at the water body\n\u2022\nTechnical flood protection\n\u2022\nPrecautionary measures in the planning area\n\u2022\nFlood forecasting\nFor all measures a statement regarding the cost-benefit ratio was given; the expected positive effect was \ncompared to the costs and the result was evaluated.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Action Plan Rur\nFlood Action Plan Rur\nCreated since 2003 \nLead by: StUA Aachen and BR K\u00f6ln\nCatchment area: 2,100 km \u00b2\nRiver length: 120 km\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDetermination of Flood Damage Potential\nHydrological\nmodel analysis\nHydraulic\ncalculation\nAcquisition of\ngeo-information\nCalculation of\nflood areas\n(depth maps)\nIdentifying the\nland use\nAcquisition of\neconomic indicators\nProvision of\ndamage functions\nComputing\nthe use-specific\namount of damage\nComputing\nuse-specific\nmonetary damages\nAnalysis and\nsummary of\nmonetary damages\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Action Plan Rur - Hydrology\nData basis for hydrological simulation: 5 catchment areas\n\u2022\nFAP (Flood Action Plan) Rur 3 part models\n\u2013 Rainfall-runoff model Rur\n\u2013 Rainfall-runoff model Wurm\n\u2013 Rainfall-runoff model Aachen\n\u2022\nConsideration of\n\u2013 FAP Inde\n\u2013 Rainfall-runoff model WVER (Talsim)\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood-Prone Areas\nObersee - state border\nto Belgium\nObermaubach - Heimbach\nJ\u00fclich -Obermaubach\nKaphof - J\u00fclich\nState border\nNetherlands - Kaphof\n17 km\n22 km\n28 km\n20 km\n25 km\nAerial survey in 1972, \nflow profile as box profile\nRIPARIA 1 project\neffective 1999-2002\nTerrestrial surveying\nin 1989\nTerrestrial surveying\nin 1991\nnothing\nWSP model 1981\nonly on paper\nRIPARIA 1 project\n2002, WSP96 format\nEffective 1989\nformat JABRON\nEffective 1991\nFormat HEC-2\nnothing\nData base for hydraulic simulations:\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDigital Elevation Models\nData base for hydraulic calculations were digital elevation models differing in terms of the collection method and \nthe raster width.\nAcquisition year\nCollection method\nRaster width\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStandards for Land Use\nWhen creating Flood Action Plans the scale of the land use model used is an essential factor.\nMicroscale, mesoscale, or macroscale is used.\nThe choice of the scale is important for: \n\u2022\nthe quality of the results (content-related, spatial)\n\u2022\nthe balance between gain of information and additional expenses \nChoice of the scale for the FAP Rur:\n\u2022\nSpatially = Microscale\n\u2022\nDamage-relevant parameters = Mesoscale\n\u2022\nDamage calculation = Microscale\n\u2022\nPresenting the results = Mesoscale\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMicroscale\nMicroscale => Individual objects \nALK data or digitization based on DGK5 / aerial photos\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMesoscale\nMesoscale => Groups of objects (entire streets, \u2026)\nATKIS / ALK data\nImage Quote: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDamage Potential Calculation\nHydrology\nProbability\nQ [m\u00b3/s]\nDamage\nevaluation\nProbability\nDamage [ \u20ac ]\nDamage calculation\nWater depth [m]\nDamage [ \u20ac ]\nRiver hydraulics\nWater level [m above sea level]\nQ [m\u00b3/s]\nYearly expected\ndamage\nReduction\nFlood\nprotection\nSource: ProAqua\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 4 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License \n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 5 - Hazard Maps and Risk Maps =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 5\nTopics:\nFlood Hazard Maps and Flood Risk Maps\nDefinitions\nMap Content and Map Types\nStructure of the Maps\nNational Geoportal of the Federal Institute of Hydrology (BfG)\nEuropean and American examples of Flood Hazard Maps and Flood Risk Maps\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\n... and you understand when and how to make use of them.\nYou are aware of the input of Flood Hazard Maps and Flood Risk Maps ...\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nYou elaborate und assess the differences of maps in different European Countries.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Maps I\nIn 2004, the German Working Group of the Federal States on Water Issues (LAWA) has published \nTools and recommendations for the implementation \nof guidelines for a future-oriented flood protection\nIt contained the following information regarding Flood Hazard Maps:\n...\n[They] describe the hazards caused by flood events as a synergy of\nprobability of occurence (return period of the event) and \nintensity (water depth, flow velocity or product of the two) \n...\nshould be created for all the areas which are vulnerable to flood damage \n(see \u00a7 31b old Federal Water Act)\n...\nare working tools for local and regional planning as well as for the water weir, civil protection \nand the insurance industry\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Maps II\nIn 2007, LAWA has furthermore elaborated recommendations for the creation of Flood Hazard Maps.\nThey include the following requirements for Flood Hazard Maps:\n...\n[They] include the determination of the flood areas during floods with low, medium \nand if necessary high probability\n...\ninclude the representation of the extent of a flooding, of the water depth and the water level \nand where applicable the flow velocity or the relevant water runoff in the most suitable scale\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Maps I\nIn addition to Flood Hazard Maps, Flood Risk Maps are supposed to represent flood-related adverse impacts. \nThis is based on those load cases that were developed in the Hazard Maps.\nAspects to be represented:\n\u2022 The number of potentially affected inhabitants\n\u2022 Type of economic activities concerned\n\u2022 Affected plants (e.g. power generation, metallurgy, mineral processing, chemical industry, waste \nmanagement)\n\u2022 Potentially affected protected areas (e.g. water protection areas, bathing waters, \nnutrient sensitive areas, conservation areas, Natura 2000 sites)\n\u2022 Areas with high bed load transport or special pollution sources\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStipulations in the Federal Water Act\nAccording to the old rules of the Federal Water Act (valid until February 2010), the flood areas were regulated in \naccordance with \u00a7 31b. \nThis included the following approaches:\n\u2022 No statement was made regarding Flood Risk Maps \n\u2022 It was determined that water bodies must be designated and announced if a large and medium-sized \n(\u201cnot only minor\") flood damage is expected\n\u2022 For such water bodies, the flood areas had to be determined and secured on a preliminary basis\n\u2022 Following deadlines for determining the flood areas were set:\n\u2013 Areas with high damage potential until May 2010\n\u2013 Areas with medium damage potential until May 2012\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nStipulations in State Water Laws in Germany\nStipulations to establish and publish Flood Hazard Maps exist\n\u2022 in Baden-Wuerttemberg\n(\u00a7 80 para. 1 in conjunction with \u00a7 77 para. 3 WG Baden-Wuerttemberg)\n\u2022 in Saxony\n(\u00a7 99b para. 2 no. 7 and para. 4 S\u00e4chsWG)\n\u2022 in other states in connection with the development of flood protection plans in accordance \nwith the old \u00a7 31 of the Federal Water Act\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nContent of Flood Hazard Maps I\nReturn period of the flood\nFlood areas for \nHQ 10/20/50\nHQ 100 and \nHQ extreme (> HQ 200)\nIntensity of flood\nWater depth classes [m]: \n0 - 0.5 / 0.5 - 1 / 1- 2 / 2 - 4 / > 4\nClasses of the flow velocity [m/s]: < 0.5 / 0.5 \u2013 2.0 / > 2.0 \nA distinction is made between results from 1D and 2D simulation models \nOther possible parameters that depict the intensity:\n\u2013 the product of the flow velocity and water depth \n(This procedure is used in Switzerland)\n\u2013 the duration of the flooding \n\u2013 the rate of rise of the flood wave\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nContent of Flood Hazard Maps II\nMain danger zones\n\u2022 Hospitals, schools\n\u2022 Dams and flood control reservoirs\n\u2022 Bridges, culverts, pipings\n\u2022 Weirs, flood polders, sluices, pump stations and pumping stations\n\u2022 Wastewater treatment plants and any water-endangered facilities\nImportant information\n\u2022 Gauge, auxiliary gauge\n\u2022 High-water marks of flooding\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nContent of Flood Hazard Maps III\nMap content according to Article 6, paragraph 5 of the EU Floods Directive:\n\u2022 Number of potentially affected inhabitants (benchmark)\n\u2022 Type of economic activities in the potentially affected area\n\u2022 Facilities according to Annex I of Directive 96/61/EC on Integrated Pollution Prevention and Control \nwhich in case of flooding might cause accidental environmental pollution as well as potentially affected \nprotected areas identified in Annex IV no. 1 section i, iii and v of the EU-WFD\n\u2022 More Information that is considered as useful such as the indication of areas where floods can occur \nwith a high content of transported sediments and debris as well as information on other significant \nsources of pollution\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nContent of Flood Hazard Maps IV\nBase maps\nDifferent maps presenting the flooded areas of a particular return period including the resulting water depths\nAdditional map\nAs additional map LAWA recommends the presentation of flood areas of different return periods without \nspecifying the water depths. Instead of the water depth zoning is introduced. This is more suitable for \ncomparisons.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Zone Maps\nSpecial case: Flood Hazard Zone Maps\nThese are subject-specific interpretations of the Flood Hazard Maps for spatial planning and regional planning.\nSubdivision into:\n\u2022 Substantial risk (red)\n\u2022 Moderate risk (blue)\n\u2022 Low risk (yellow)\n\u2022 Residual risk (hatched)\nImage Quote: Website of the Environmental Agency of Saxony\nProbability\nIntensitiy\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDeterminants of Hazard Maps\nWSPWIN\nHYDRO-AS 2D\nHQ x\nLand parcel lists\nWater depth maps\nRetention volume\nGIS\nGIS\nGIS\nGIS\nDTM\nImage Quote: Spanknebel\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nBasic Hydraulic Information\nSurveying and Digital Terrain Model (DTM)\n\u2022 Measuring channel profiles \n(every 100-150 m longitudinal distance, \nlesser distance depending on requirements)\n\u2022 Measuring special profiles (dams, bridges, etc.)\n\u2022 Determining the bottom slope and recording the water level at the day of measurement\n\u2022 Aerial surveying with 60 % longitudinal and 30 % transversal overlap \n(altitude \uf0a31000 m, accuracy \u00b1 10 cm) \nor aerial laser scanner survey\n\u2022 Generation of DTM \nor make use of the official DTM of the land surveying offices\n 219,00 [m+NN] \n WSP-H\u00f6he \n WSP-HOEHE NN+m \n Trennfl\u00e4chen \n Durchstr\u00f6mte Bereiche \n Gel\u00e4ndeh\u00f6he \n Station \n [m+NN] \n [-] \n [-] \n [m+NN] \n [-] \n -6,07 \n 220,23 \n 4,95 \n 220,24 \n -7,70 \n 1,00 \n 6,64 \n 2,00 \n -28,78 \n 222,51 \n 36,63 \n 221,79 \n 222,51 \n 222,24 \n 222,12 \n 222,01 \n 220,83 \n 220,23 \n 219,62 \n 219,54 \n 219,83 \n 220,91 \n 221,79 \n 221,78 \n 221,79 \n -28,78 \n -22,41 \n -14,58 \n -10,61 \n -7,70 \n -6,07 \n -2,77 \n 1,21 \n 4,33 \n 6,64 \n 9,80 \n 17,07 \n 36,63 \nImage quote: Spannknebel\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nProcedure of Calculation\n\u2022 Calculation of load cases: HQ10 - HQ20 - HQ50 / HQ100 / HQextreme\n\u2022 Possible input for the extreme value statistical discharges:\nExtreme value statistics for selected gauges [with long time series]\nHydrological longitudinal sections  \nRegionalization process  \nRainfall-Runoff Modeling\n\u2022 Using a hydrodynamic 1D model for steady or unsteady flow conditions\n\u2022 Alternatively: Application of a 2D model in case of unclear flow conditions\n\u2022 Hydraulic calculation for the bankful discharge and water level calculation for the listed load cases\n\u2022 Intersecting water levels and valley profiles using GIS\n\u2022 Plausibility check, adjusting the flooding limits to the topographic map \n(if appropriate on-site calibration)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPotential Users and Standards I\nWater management authorities (1: 5.000 to 1: 10.000)\n\u2022 for flood control plans and flood control concepts as well as for priorities for action regarding flood protection\n\u2022 for the reactivation of retention areas\n\u2022 for the determination regarding the handling of water-hazardous substances\nPlanning authorities (1: 50.000 to 1: 100.000)\nConsideration of vulnerable areas by determining priority areas and reservation areas in the Regional Development Plans\nObjectives:\nSecuring and recovering flood plains\nAvoiding potential danger to life of the affected people\nReducing flood damage\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPotential Users and Standards II\nDistricts and municipalities (1: 1.000 to 1: 25.000)\n\u2022 Basis for planning for the settlement development, for land management and building precautions (urban land-use \nplanning)\n\u2022 As a basis for averting danger and civil protection\n\u2022 Identification of risk sites and evacuation routes\n\u2022 Deployment of personnel and material resources\n\u2022 Developing additional lines of defense\nInsurance industry (1: 10.000)\nImprovement of zoning system (Z\u00dcRS) for the classification of the insured persons in hazard classes\nAffected (1: 1.000 to 1: 10.000)\nBuilding, behavioral and risk precautions\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExpulsion of Inundation Zones in NRW\nImage Quote: Website of BR Cologne for Flood Areas \nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExtract of the Stipulations I\n\u201cFlood areas are significant areas for flood control and for water protection. They must preserve their function as \nnatural retention areas.\nActivities and changes in the earth\u2019s surface in legal flood areas require a permit in accordance with \u00a7\u00a7 78 \nFederal Water Act (WHG), 113 State Water Act (LWG) by the competent authority.\u201d\n\u201cThe designation of these areas has to be published in the official journal of the regional government of Cologne \nin the form of a proper administrative regulation, including an overview map at a scale of 1:25.000 or 1:50.000.\u201c\n\u201cThe designation of a flood area in accordance with \u00a7 112 para. 1 no. 5 in conjunction with \u00a7 14 para. 3 \nLWG lasts forty years.\u201c\nSource: Internet page of BR Cologne regarding floodplains\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExtract of the Stipulations II\n\u201cThe regional government of Cologne has to set the legal mandate for fixing of areas with a potentially significant \nflood risk as flood areas by the end of 2013. This concerns areas that are inundated by a 100-year flood. \nThese expulsions inform the affected population and the public authorities about the propagation and the rise of \nwater level within a 100-year flood. \nThe goal of the stipulation is to inform preventively, to preserve the status quo and to prevent a worsening of the \nflood risk by prohibiting further structural works. Each structural change can cause a deterioration of the high \nwater runoff. \nMoreover, structural changes may lead to the flooding of previously unaffected areas and / or an increase in the \nflood risk and the damage caused by it. This can be counteracted by the fixing of flood areas.\u201c \nSource: Internet page of BR Cologne regarding floodplains\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample Calculation for a Compensation\nBase area along Ackerbrucher Street (four\nliving units) according to loccation plan \nb = 861 m\u00b2 / 44 m = 19.6 m\nWater depth according to hydraulic detection of\nthe BR Cologne \nt mean = 19 cm\nt max. = 61 cm\nResulting compensating volume\nV =F * t mean\n= 2,266 * 0.19 \n= 430 [m\u00b3]\n=> Resulting base area for the retention basin\nWidth of the strip for a retention basin\n(for a land width of 44 m)\nh = 0.50 m\nFretention = 430 m\u00b3 / 0.5 m = 861 m\u00b2\nF = 2,266 m\u00b2\nAssumed filling depth of the retention basin\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Alert in Saxony\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nGerman Geoportal for Hazard Maps and Risk Maps \nThe Federal Institute of Hydrology has set up \na Geoportal on which the nationwide flood \nhazard and flood risk maps can be viewed. \nImage Quote: WasserBLIcK.NET\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Map Cologne \u2013 HQ100\nImage Quote: Flussgebiete NRW, MULNV\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Map Cologne \u2013 HQextreme\nImage Quote: Flussgebiete NRW, MULNV\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map Cologne \u2013 HQ100\nImage Quote: Flussgebiete NRW, MULNV\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map Cologne \u2013 HQextreme\nImage Quote: Flussgebiete NRW, MULNV\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Map Dresden \u2013 HQ100\nImage Quote: Umweltamt Sachsen\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Map Dresden \u2013 HQextreme\nGefahr HQ extrem - Elbe\nImage Quote: Umweltamt Sachsen\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map Dresden \u2013 HQ100\nImage Quote: Umweltamt Sachsen\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Map Passau \u2013 HQ100\nImage Quote: Bayerisches Landesamt f\u00fcr Umwelt\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map Passau \u2013 HQ100\nImage Quote: Bayerisches Landesamt f\u00fcr Umwelt\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map: London, England\nImage Quote: https://flood-warning-information.service.gov.uk\n\u2022\nTarget group: general public\n\u2022\nEnables display of three flood events. \nFlood risks from:\n\uf02dRivers and sea\n\uf02dSurface water\n\uf02dReservoirs\n\u2022\nThe flood risk categories very low, low, medium \nand high are not further specified.\n\u2022\nShows extend and estimated depth\nand flow at monitoring stations\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map: Surface Water London, England\nImage Quote: https://flood-warning-information.service.gov.uk\n\u2022\nFlood risk categories: \nHigh, medium, low and very low\n\u2022\nExtend, depth and velocity can be shown\n\uf02dDepth is shown for\n< 300 mm\n300-900 mm\n>900 mm\n\uf02dVelocity is shown for\n< 0.25 m/s\n> 0.25 m/s\n\uf02dFlow direction is indicated by arrows\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard Map: Flood Maps for planning London, England\nImage Quote: https://flood-map-for-planning.service.gov.uk\n\u2022\nTarge group: land-use planning (rivers and sea)\n\u2022\nProvides information on:\n\uf02dFlood zones\n\uf02dFlood risk assessment\n\uf02dLevel of flood protection\n\uf02dFlood defence lines\n\u2022\nShows flood storage areas\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Warning Map: London, England II\n\u2022 Target group: residents\n\u2022 Shows if flood warnings are available\n\u2022 Differentiates between warnings and alerts\n\u2013 Warnings: when flooding is expected\n\u2013 Alerts: when flooding is possible\nImage Quote: Environment Agency, England\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Hazard and Risk Maps: Belfast, Northern Ireland\n\u2022 ArcGIS-based online map\n\u2022 Each square indicates an area for which an \nofficial flood map (PDF) is available\n\u2022 Flood hazard maps for rivers, sea and \nsurface water\n\u2022 Flood risk maps for rivers and sea\nImage Quote: http://riversagency.maps.arcgis.com\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Management Plans Scotland\n\u2022 Local Flood Risk Management plans for \n14 distritcs have been derived\n\u2022 Local authorities have developed \ncomplementary local flood plans until 2022\n\u2022 Actions have to be taken until 2028\nImage Quote: https://www2.sepa.org.uk/frmplans/\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map: Paris, France \nImage Quote:http://www.georisques.gouv.fr\n\u2022 Users can select their location on a \nmap or by coordinates\n\u2022 Location based risk information are \ngiven\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Management in the Netherlands\n\u2026 a matter of national survival\n60% of population live in\nand \n70% of GDP is produced in \nareas between 1 and 6.5 meters below mean sea level\nImage Quote: http://www.swartvast.nl\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Map: The Netherlands\nImage Quote: http://www.risicokaart.nl\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n\u2022\nResponse to floods before 1953 \nStrengthening the levees \n(Reference point: highest observed water level)\n\u2022\nAfter 1953 \nRevolution in thinking \nfrom reactive response to proactive protection \n(Costs of reinforcements are weighed against the reduction \nin flood risk)\nFlood Risk Management in the Netherlands\nImage Quote: TU Delft\nThe Strom Surge of 1953\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Management in the Netherlands\nStatutory flood protection standards\naccording to The Water Act of 2009 \nImage Quote: VNK Report\nThe Flood Risk in the Netherlands project \n\"Veiligheid Nederland in Kaart\u201c (VNK)\ncalculated the probability of flooding and flood risk\nfor 58 levee systems\n3 measures of risk\n\u2022 Economic risk\n\u2022 Idividual risk (IR)\n\u2022 Societal risk\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Management in the Netherlands\nEconomic risk [\u20ac/ha/year]\nSocietal risk\nNumber of deaths as a \ndirect result of a flood\nshown in a graph\nIndividual risk [annual probability]\nImage Quote: VNK Report\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Risk Management in Europe\nFlood Risk Areas Viewer for mapping in Europe\nImage Quote: WISE Freshwater. Flood Risk area Viewer\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nUSA: IOWA Flood Information System\nImage Quote: IFIS\nIn December 2021 the Iowa Flood Center introduced the \nIowa Flood Information System.\nCitizens can inform themselves about upcoming flood events \nat any time with the help of the web-based system.\nA map service for inundations maps and for flood alerts is \nprovided.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nIOWA Flood Information System: Indundation Maps\nImage Quote: IFIS\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nIOWA Flood Information System: Draft Flood Hazard Maps & Risk Management Maps\nThe system also offers Draft \nFlood Hazard Maps as well \nas Risk Management Maps.\nImage Quote: IFIS\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 5 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License \n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 6 - Hydraulic Models =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 6\nTopics:\nHydraulic Modeling: 1D versus 2D\nModeling Concepts\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\nYou understand the fundamental differences between 1D and 2D modeling in terms of the outcomes\n(water levels and flow velocities).\nYou rank the results of hazard maps and risk maps in terms of hydraulic fundamentals and \nyou evaluate them correctly on a factual basis.\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nInitial Situation 1D Modeling\nCross \nsection 1\nCross \nsection 2\n+\n+\n+\n+\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCross Section\nWL\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDivision into Main Channel and Flood Plains I\nkSt = 30 - 40\nkSt = 5 - 8\nkSt = 5 - 8\nV = kSt x I \u00bd x R 2/3 \nFlow velocity:\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDivision into Main Channel and Flood Plains II\nkSt = 30 - 40\nkSt = 5 - 8\nkSt = 5 - 8\nV = kSt x I \u00bd x R 2/3 \nFlow velocity:\nV [m/s]\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nResult of 1D Modeling\n+\n+\n+\n+\nResult:\nimplausible velocities\nin the flood plains \n(because v can only be\ndetermined along the cross profile sections)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nInitial Situation 2D Modeling\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\nrecreating breaklines\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nTriangulation\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nResulting 2D-Velocity Vectors\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\n+\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample of a 2D Simulation (Waterdepth) \nVideo Quote: ARGE Wasser\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample of a 2D Simulation (sheer stress at river bottom) \nVideo Quote: ARGE Wasser\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCase Study Main I\nImage Quote: Prof. Disse\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nGauges Schw\u00fcrbitz and Mainleus\nWehr \nBurgkunstadt\nHochstadt\nRothwind\nMaineck\n1 km\nSchw\u00fcrbitz\nMainleus\nGauge Mainleus: \nAEO = 1169 km\u00b2; MQ = 14,1 m\u00b3/s; MHQ = 150 m\u00b3/s; HHQ = 357 m\u00b3/s \nGauge Schw\u00fcrbitz: \nAEO = 2419 km\u00b2; MQ = 29,7 m\u00b3/s; MHQ = 303 m\u00b3/s; HHQ = 764 m\u00b3/s\nImage Quote: Prof. Disse\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n1D Simulation\nImage Quote: Prof. Disse\nPros:\n\u2022 Low computation time \n(for both steady and \nunsteady flow)\n\u2022 Very good modeling of \n1D discharge patterns\nCons:\n\u2022 Flood plain runoff is difficult to \ndepict (potentially inaccurate)\n\u2022 Cross flows are not \nconsidered\n\u2022 Simplifications required\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n1D Model II\nWork Steps:\n\u2022 Division of the river channel (compact/ segmented) \n\u2022 Creation of a channel system including buildings\n\u2022 Mapping of short circuit flows and possible flows around buildings due to river branches\n\u2022 Implementation of possible breaklines (road embankments)\n\u2022 Division of the channel system into sections of varying roughness\n\u2022 Calibration\n\u2022 Validation\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n2D Simulation\nImage Quote: Prof. Disse\nPros:\n\u2022 Very good simulation of \nthe flow in the flood plains\n\u2022 Higher accuracy of \nthe runoff simulation\n\u2022 Well suited for retention \ncalculations\nCons:\n\u2022 High computational effort\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\n2D Model II\nWork Steps:\n\u2022 Creation of the river channel network \n\u2022 Creation of a flood plain network taking the breaklines into account\n\u2022 Generation of an overall network of river channel network and flood plain network\n\u2022 Implementation of structures and buildings into the overall network\n\u2022 Division of the channel system into sections of varying roughness\n\u2022 Calibration\n\u2022 Validation\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHN - Modeling Concepts III\n1D / 2D simulation (hybrid)\nSOBEK\nAdvantages of 1D and 2D \nmodels but no momentum \nexchange!\nImage Quote: Prof. Disse\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHN - Modeling Concepts IV\n1D / 2D simulation (hybrid) \nMIKE\nLinking line (MIKEFlood) \nImage Quote: Prof. Disse\nAdvantages of 1D and 2D \nmodels but no momentum \nexchange!\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nUncertain Parameters\nCross profiles: \nSeveral years old, changes after each flooding\nRoughness: \nIS calibrated at events \n(Level measurement containing errors, especially in flood events)\nVegetation or state of the river bed (especially in the flood plain) is not stationary\nDigital Terrain Model (DTM): Laser scanning contained errors\nRunoff Q: \nThe statistically determined value of the T-annual runoff is uncertain \n(has not been the subject of the investigation)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nHistorical Preparation of DTM for Hydraulic Simulations\nAerial stereo photo from aerial survey for\nthe water management administration\nPhotogrammetric evaluation\nMapping\nland cover\nDigital Terrain \nModel\nComputational mesh\nfor hydraulic modeling (1D & 2D)\nSlide Source: Gabriele Merz\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCurrent Preparation of DTM for Hydraulic Simulations\nSlide Source: Gabriele Merz\nLaser scanner \naerial survey of the \nsurveying authority\nAerial photos of the\nBavaria aerial\nsurvey, satellite\nimages, ATKis\nDigital Terrain \nModel with constant\ngrid points\nAutomated mapping\nland cover\nAutomatic thinning\nComputational mesh\nfor 2D hydraulic modeling\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Scan\nApplication of 2D modeling on the basis of laser scanning data\nLarge-area test of new methods\n\u2022 Adapted solutions (best practice)\nImproved processing of basic data\n\u2022 Automatic thinning DTM\n\u2022 Classification land cover\n\u2022 Profiles\nFaster and improved mesh generation for the 2D hydrodynamic modeling\nSensitivity analyses to optimize time and expenses\nDevelopment of the Web Mapping Service\nSlide Source: Gabriele Merz\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nProcessing of the Terrain Structures\nThinning of 1m laser data and generation of relevant terrain structures.\nThe 2D computational meshes are directly generated from laser data.\nIn several internal calculation steps, the terrain structure and the terrain edges are detected from the 1m grid. \nThese later serve as a basis for triangulation of the computational mesh.\nSlide Source: Gabriele Merz\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLand Cover\nDetermination of the hydraulically relevant land cover classes by ...\n\u2022 Reclassification of ATKIS-Data (GIS routine)\n\u2022 Interpretation of analog and digital multispectral earth observation data (IKONOS, HRSC)\n\u2022 Sensitivity analyses as part of the hydraulic modeling\n\u2022 Method optimization\n\u2022 Roughness maps\nSlide Source: Gabriele Merz\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 6 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License \n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 7 - Mobile Flood Protection =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 7\nTopics:\nFlood Protection: Case Study Cologne\nMobile Flood Protection Units \nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nYou apply appropriate methods in order to prepare and train staff for their tasks \nduring operational emergency.\nYou understand and solve the tasks and problems that occur during operations \nof mobile flood protection units.\nYou know the possibilities and limitations of the use of mobile flood protection elements.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nReasons for Mobil Flood Protection in Cologne\nThe city of Cologne suffered sever floods \nthree times within a timespan of 10 years. \nThe river Rhine flooded the city in 1993, \n1995 and again in 1999.\nIn 1993 a water level of 10,63 m related to \nthe Cologne water depth gauge emerged \nand 15 month later, in 1995 a water level of \n10,69 occurred.\nAfter these three flood events the \nadministration set up a lasting concept for \nflood protection and measures to reduce \nflood risks [by installing mobil flood \nprotection units].\nImage Quote:  StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCologne Christmas Flood 1993\nVideo Quote:  WDR\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFloodprotected Area \nImage Quote:  StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFigures of the Operational Flood Protection in Cologne I\n\u2022\nBank length of the Rhine in the urban area:\n69.91 km\n\u2022\nRiparian area to be protected up to 11.30 m Cologne Gauge:\n32.2 km\n\u2022\nRiparian area to be protected up to 11.90 m Cologne Gauge:\n37.3 km\n\u2022\noverall length of all mobile flood protection units:                                         \n10.3 km\n\u2022\nLength of flood footbridges:\n~2.00 km\n\u2022\nFerry service with 10 boats and 3 Unimogs in 3 city districts\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFigures of the Operational Flood Protection in Cologne II\n\u2022 Total quantity of pillars:\n3851 units\n\u2022 Total amount of stoplogs:\n39405 units\n91 % have standard lengths of 2 m or 3 m\n9 % have special lengths \n(81 various lengths from 491 mm up to 5016 mm)\n\u2022 Overall length of stoplogs:\n93 km\n\u2022 Special closing units \n43 units\n(for windows, doors and underground car parks):          \n\u2022 Total area of \u200bthe mobile elements:\n14,510 m\u00b2\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nSituation of Deposits\nWastewater Treatment Plant Langel\nSt.-Leonardus-Road\nWastewater Treatment Plant Stammheim\nRodenkirchener Bridge\nWastewater Treatment Plant Rodenkirchen\nDeutz Bridge\nWermelskircher Road\nAnkergasse Z\u00fcndorf\n8 deposits\n[ca. 7000 m\u00b2 area] \n1 free warehouse\n[ca. 2000 m\u00b2 area]\n1 barn\n[ca. 200 m\u00b2 area]\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nSituation in a Deposit\nImage Quote:  StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Protection Sections \nPFA 12\nretention area\nLangel / L\u00fclsdorf\nNo mobile flood\nprotection systems\nPFA 13\nLangel\n5 gates\nConstruction\ncompany: SMK\nPFA 14\nZ\u00fcndorf-Marktplatz\n2 gates, mobile wall\nConstruction\ncompanies: Tamco, \nMeyer\nPFA 1\nGodorf - S\u00fcrth\n4 gates, mobile wall\nConstruction\ncompanies:\nTamco. StEB\nPFA 2\nS\u00fcrther M\u00fchle -\nPflasterhof\n11 gates\nConstruction\ncompany: Caspar\nImage Quote:  StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDetailed Location Map PFA 1\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\n3\n4\n5\n2\n1\nMobile wall \u201cAuf dem \nH\u00fcgel\u201c\nPos. 1-46\n11.18 m\u00b7kp (48.96 mNN)\nDoor locks above\n\"Fronhofstr.\"\nPos. 47-48\n9.72 m\u00b7kp (47.44 mNN)\nDoor locks above\n\"Fronhofstr.\"\nPos. 49-50\n9.72 m\u00b7kp (47.44 mNN)\nDoor locks above\n\"Fronhofstr.\"\nPos. 51-52\n9.73 m\u00b7kp (47.45 mNN)\nDoor locks on \n\"Fronhofstr.\"\nPos. 53-54\n9.90 m\u00b7kp (47.62 mNN)\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nOrganization of the Operational Flood Protection\nIn charge of sections\n87 technicians + StEB engineers\nLogistic leader\n(external)\nTB-4\nTB\nFlood Protection Centre\nExecutive Board\n15 construction companies\n+ StEB + THW\n7 carrier companies\nSpecialized vehicles\nFood and drinks\nFerry service DLRG\nGuarding\nTraffic measures / Barriers\nQuote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExercises of Flood Protection Operations\nExercise in 2009: \nArea Cologne-M\u00fclheim and Cologne-Stammheim; \n8.5 % of all mobile elements were assembled\nLarge-scale exercise in 2009: Area Cologne-Neustadt-S\u00fcd to Cologne-Neustadt-Nord; \n28 % of all mobile elements were assembled\nLarge-scale exercise in 2010: Area Cologne-Wei\u00df and Cologne-Rodenkirchen;\n12.5 % \u200bof all mobile elements were assembled\nFloods in 2011: \nEntire urban area (but predominantly the left side of the Rhine); \nabout 15 % of all mobile elements were assembled\nExercise in 2011: \nArea Cologne-Poll to Cologne-Deutz; 3 % of all mobile elements were assembled\nExercise in 2012: \nPFA 5, 6, 16/2 as well as the retention area; L\u00fclsdorf/ Langel (PFA 12); \n=> Scenario exercise\nExercise in 2013: \nPFA 8 and 13; => Exercise purely for the assembling\nExercise in 2014: \nMiddle of PFA 7 and 15; => Scenario exercise\nExercise in 2015: \nPFA 1, 2, 9, 11; => Assembling Exercise\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFlood Protection in Cologne\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMobile Flood Protection Units: A case study\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLateral Guide Rails\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExposing Threads\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCleaning Threads\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCleaning Guide Rails and the Sealing\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMounting the Pillar\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nApplying a Torque\nA torque of 150 Nm must be applied\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nInserting the Bottom Stoplog\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nInserting the Bottom Stoplog\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nFixing the Pressing Tool\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nTightening the Stoplogs\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nBottom Sealing\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nMounting a Back Support\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample of a final Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample of a final Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nAssembly Scenario\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nChaos during the Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Assembly\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Dismantling\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nImpressions of the Dismantling\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nImage Quote: StEB Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDismantling the Wall Elements [no go]\nImage Quote:  IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRisks while Dismantling the Wall Elements [no go]\nImage Quote:  IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPotentially damaging the Sealing [no go]\nImage Quote:  IN\nX\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPractical Exercises performed by Students in Cologne\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPractical Exercises performed by Students at the Institute\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPractical Exercises performed by Students at the Institute\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nConstruction of a mobile flood protection Unit in Virtual Reality\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nSpecial Training Support by Blended Learing\nImage Quote:  IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nTraining Media to assemble the Mobile Flood Protection Units\nImage Quote: IN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 7 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License \n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n\n\n===== Lecture 12 - Torrential Rain =====\nCourse Flood Risk Management\nLecture 12\nTopics:\nTorrential rain \nRainfall Radar\nRadar Online Authentication\nThe European Flood Awareness System\nCivil Protection and Disaster Management in Germany\nUse case low-pressure system \u201eBernd\u201c: 12. - 15. Juli 2021\nEU project RAINMAN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nLearning Objectives of the Lecture\nYou know where to find measures to reduce the risk of heavy rainfall that have already been tested out.\nYou understand the principle of rainfall radar.\nYou know the magnitudes of heavy rainfall events.\nanalyze\napply\nunderstand\nremember\ncreate\nassess\nYou understand the organisational structure of civil protection.\nYou are familiar with the different systems for warning of heavy rainfall events.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nWhat is meant by torrential rain?\n\"Rain [...] which has a high precipitation intensity [...] in relation to its duration and therefore occurs infrequently, \ne.g. on average no more than twice a year.\" [DIN 4049-3 1994]\n\"Heavy rainfall is when there are large amounts of precipitation per unit of time. It usually falls from convective \nclouds (e.g. cumulonimbus clouds). Heavy rain can occur anywhere and lead to rapidly rising water levels and \n(or) flooding. Heavy rain is often accompanied by soil erosion.\" [DWD Weather Dictionary]\n\"A marked precipitation event occurring during a period of time of 1h, 3h, 6h, 12h, 24h or 48 hours with a total \nprecipitation exceeding a certain threshold defined for a given location.\" [WMO 2015]\nNote: There is no universal definition of heavy rain!\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDifferent ways of defining heavy rainfall events\nUsual for the description are:\n\u2022\nThreshold values\n\u2022\nPercentile method\n\u2022\nRecurrence intervals\n\u2022\nHeavy rain indices\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDefinition via Threshold Values by DWD & WMO\nThe German Weather Service warns of such events in three stages.\nDistinctive weather warning: Warning event heavy rainfall\nPrecipitation amount 15 - 25 l/m\u00b2 in 1 h or 20 - 35 l/m\u00b2 in 6 h\nSevere weather warning: Warning event Heavy rainfall\nPrecipitation amount > 25 - 40 l/m\u00b2 in 1 h or > 35 - 60 l/m\u00b2 in 6 h\nWarning of extreme thunderstorm: Warning event Extremely heavy rainfall\nPrecipitation amount > 40 l/m\u00b2 in 1 h or > 60 l/m\u00b2 in 6 h\nThe World Meteorological Organization defines a heavy rainfall if \u2265 50 mm of precipitation has fallen in the last \n24h.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nNational Warnings in Germany\nIn Germany, the German Meteorological Service [DWD] is responsible for producing precipitation forecasts. \nThe results of the forecasts are made available by the DWD in its warning weather app.\nDWD app for Germany with precipitation radar information, weather alerts and warnings about floods, \nstorm surges and avalanches\nWarnwetter\nIn addition, this information is integrated into the NINA app of the Federal Office of Civil Protection and Disaster \nMangement.\nApp of the Federal Office for Civil Protection and Disaster Management with civil protection including\nalerts, weather warnings and flood information [has been installed roundabout 10 Mio. times in \nGermany]\nNINA\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRainfall Radar\nDue to the areal coverage, rain radars can map the dynamics and structure of the rain event.\nThe radar unit emits radar waves ...\n... radar waves are reflected by the \nprecipitation particles\nThe more water droplets, snow crystals or ice \nparticles there are in the atmosphere, the more \nradar waves are reflected.\n360\u00b0\nThe radar system can be used to determine the precipitation \ncontent of a rain event.\n=> the more precipitation particles, the more reflection.\nThe distance of the precipitation particles to the radar station results \nfrom the time difference between sending and receiving the radar \nwaves.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRainfall Radar: Principle\nVideo Quote: MeteoSuisse\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nWeather Radar: How does it work?\nVideo Quote: BOM Bureau of Meteorology Australia\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDWD: Example of a radar recording and national radar network\nPicture Quote: DWD\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPrinciple of radar precipitation measurement\nPE = Receiving power \nC = Device constant\nU = Rayleigh approximation\nfactor\nr = Target distance\nZ = Reflectivity factor\nPulse volume V\nOpening angle \u0398 = 1\u00b0\nPulse volume height c*\u03c4\nPE = C*U\u00b2*1/r\u00b2*z [W]\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nPrinciple of radar precipitation measurement\nPrecipitation measurements can be used to obtain both qualitative and quantitative information on the spatial \ndistribution of precipitation. \nThe reflection of the radar's backscattered energy can be used to draw conclusions about the precipitation \nintensity: \nZ = Reflectivity factor (radar echo) \nI = Precipitation intensity [mm/h]\na,b = Parameter constants\nb ~ 1,6\na = 140 in drizzle\na = 200 on average\na = 500 during thunderstorms\nZ = a I b\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nExample: Cold front\nExample of a radar image of a cold front with heavy rain showers.\nThe showers run in lines across the catchment area.\nPicture Quote: Meteorological Institute of the University of Bonn\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRADOLAN (Radar Online Authentication)\nThus, precipitation radar does not directly measure the amount or \nintensity of precipitation. \nIn this respect, information from ground-based precipitation \ngauges (ombrometers) is always necessary to align the data of the \ncalculated precipitation intensities (adaptation of the radar \ninformation to the data of the ombormeters).\nFor this purpose, the data recorded at a total of 17 weather radars \nof the DWD are compared with hourly measured precipitation data \nin the RADOLAN system.\nThe result is high-resolution precipitation intensities.\nTime update: every 10 minutes \nSpatial resolution: 1km\u00b2\nPicture Quote: DWD\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRADOLAN (Radar Online Authentication)\nThe figure illustrates the connection between the radar network and the network of \nombrometer stations used. \nAt the edges of the FRG, precipitation stations from surrounding countries are also \nused.\nPicture Quote: DWD\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRainfall radar data worldwide\nYou can also get a global overview of the current precipitation conditions via free tools.\nPicture Quote: WetterOnline\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nEFAS: The European Flood Awareness System\nThe European Flood Awareness System has been installed after the 2002 flood catastrophy that took place in \nGermany, Austria and the Czech Republic.\nThe aim of EFAS is to savegarde the european citizens against floods all over europe.\nTo achieve this goal flood forecasts on an european scale are designed and the information is made available for \nnational institutions (not for the general public). \nIn Germany the forecasts are directed towards the flood protection centres of all 16 federal states.\nPicture Quote: EFAS\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nEFAS Map viewer\nThe EFAS real time forcasts are not \naccessible by general public but \nEFAS partners only.\nPicture Quote: EFAS\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDisaster management (in Germany)\nIn Germany, the task of warning of \ndisasters and general hazards is carried \nout by the federal states and their \ndisaster control authorities. \nThe federal government, on the other \nhand, is responsible for civil protection, \nwhich takes effect in the event of \ndefence.  \nPicture Quote: BBK\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nDisaster management (in Germany)\nThe disaster management is usually carried out by the interior departments of the state governments and their \nsituation centres. \nIn addition to these higher disaster control authorities, there is a lower disaster control authority at the municipal \nlevel. \nThere, coordination is carried out by the mayors or district administrators of the districts. This group of people \nalso assumes political responsibility for disaster management.\nAt the municipal level, the following organisations are involved in disaster situations:\nFire brigades, German Red Cross Organisation, Arbeiter-Samariter-Bund, DLRG, Johanniter-Unfall-Hilfe, \nMalteser Hilfsdienst.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nUse case low-pressure system \u201eBernd\u201c: 12. - 15. Juli 2021\nBildzitat: DWD, Hydrometeorologie\nPicture Quotes: DWD, Hydrometeorologie\nDWD Station Aachen-Orsbach: 55 l/m\u00b2 on 13. Juli\n98 l/m\u00b2 on 14. Juli \nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nUse case low-pressure system \u201eBernd\u201c: 12. - 15. Juli 2021\nPicture Quote: DWD, Hydrometeorologie\nThe low-pressure system \"Bernd\" encountered an initial situation in \nwhich the soils only had very low storage capacities. \nThe DWD warned of these heavy rainfall \namounts at an early stage.\nSee the videos on the DWD's \"Severe \nWeather Channel\" on Youtube.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nEFAS: additional specifications in context of low-pressure system \u201eBernd\u201c\nSome quotes of the EFAS webside concerning the low-pressure system \u201eBernd\u201c:\n\u201cEFAS produces twice-daily updated hydrological predictions for riverine and flash floods across Europe. \nThese are analysed by trained hydrologists and, based on standardised criteria, EFAS flood forecast information, \ncalled \u2018EFAS flood notifications\u2019, are issued.\u201d\n\u201cEFAS flood notifications are issued based on the type of flooding (e.g. riverine or flash flood), its probability of \nexceeding specific notification criteria (e.g. probability for the predicted river discharge to exceed a 5-year return \nperiod) and other criteria such as the size of the river.\u201d\n\u201cEFAS flood notifications contain an indication of the potentially affected larger region or river/tributary section and \na very short and basic information on the predicted probabilities to exceed a certain flood return period. \nFurthermore, there is an advisory message to follow a link to access the more detailed, regularly updated flood \nforecast information displayed in the EFAS web portal.\u201d\n\u201cOnce an EFAS notification has been received, the relevant national authority is advised to connect to the EFAS \nmap viewer for a more detailed forecast information, and to analyse the situation together with the available \nnational or local early warning information, to decide on the next actions.\u201d\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nGerman Meteorological Service: Severe weather warning from July 12th 2021\nVideo Quote: DWD Youtube-Kanal\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nGerman Meteorological Service: Extrem weather warning from July 13th 2021\nVideoQuote: DWD Youtube-Kanal\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nCase study low-pressure system \u201cBernd\u201d\nThe low-pressure systen \u201eBernd\u201c has shown that it is not good enough to offer information regarding upcoming\ntorrential rain and floods on the internet or via apps.\nThat is why in Germany the administration decided to implement of a general cell broadcasting system (starting in \n2022) so that everyone owning a phone would automaticaly be informed in case of a catastrophy.\nThe tecnology already exists since the nineteens and many countries [like the netherlands] already implemented\nit for reasons of informing societies.\nIn case of a warning a text message is displayed and a warning tone can be added optionally. This service even\nworks when the mobil is switched to mute.\nThe information ist send to every phone that is within a specified radio cell.\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRAINMAN\nThe RAINMAN project supports regional authorities and stakeholders how to best deal with heavy rain risks.\nAs a result of multiple research projects RAINMAN designed a tool that is offering 100 measures to reduce risk.\nThese measures have been tested in multiple practical approaches.\nThe measures cover:  Buildings\nSettelment Areas\nFarmland\nForests\nWatercourses\nRisk Communication\nEmergency Management\nPicture Quote: RAINMAN\nCourse Flood Risk Management | Lecture 12 |Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nThis material is part of the Creative Commons License \n\u201cAttribution 4.0 international\u201d\nPermitted:\nShare \u2014 copy and redistribute the material in any medium or format\nAdapt \u2014 remix, transform, and build upon the material for any purpose, even commercially\nYou have to quote the name of the author\nhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\nReference Quote: Univ.-Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken\nRWTH Aachen University\nCreative Commons License 4.0\n";


const SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You are a helpful study assistant for the course "Flood Risk Management" at RWTH Aachen University (Prof. Dr.-Ing. Heribert Nacken). The student has an exam in less than 48 hours.

Your knowledge comes from the complete lecture slides (provided below) covering 8 lectures. Answer questions clearly and concisely in English. Use concrete examples from the lectures when possible. If the student asks something not covered in the material, say so.

When explaining concepts:
- Be clear and beginner-friendly
- Use bullet points for structure
- Reference specific lectures when relevant
- Connect concepts across lectures to build understanding

LECTURE CONTENT:
${KNOWLEDGE_BASE}`;

exports.handler = async (event) => {
  const headers = {
    'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*',
    'Access-Control-Allow-Headers': 'Content-Type',
    'Access-Control-Allow-Methods': 'POST, OPTIONS',
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
  };

  if (event.httpMethod === 'OPTIONS') {
    return { statusCode: 200, headers, body: '' };
  }

  if (event.httpMethod !== 'POST') {
    return { statusCode: 405, headers, body: JSON.stringify({ error: 'Method not allowed' }) };
  }

  try {
    const { messages } = JSON.parse(event.body);
    const apiKey = process.env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY;

    if (!apiKey) {
      return { statusCode: 500, headers, body: JSON.stringify({ error: 'API key not configured' }) };
    }

    const response = await fetch('https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'x-api-key': apiKey,
        'anthropic-version': '2023-06-01',
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({
        model: 'claude-sonnet-4-20250514',
        max_tokens: 1024,
        system: SYSTEM_PROMPT,
        messages: messages,
      }),
    });

    const data = await response.json();

    if (!response.ok) {
      return { statusCode: response.status, headers, body: JSON.stringify({ error: data.error?.message || 'API error' }) };
    }

    return {
      statusCode: 200,
      headers,
      body: JSON.stringify({ reply: data.content[0].text }),
    };
  } catch (err) {
    return { statusCode: 500, headers, body: JSON.stringify({ error: err.message }) };
  }
};
